<font color="#FF0000">UNITED WE STAND!</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 19 10:57:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Does anyone remember the kind of fear that gets up in your throat...where you try to stare a hole through the dark...you can hear your own heart beat..vigilance is not a strong enough word to summarize the intensity!  Then it comes!  That dreaded sound of V.C. or NVA approaching...you hear sounds in the wire...infintestimaly small sounds roar in your ears..frantically you try to alert everyone without making noise or you chose to initiate the attack with your M-16, M-60, or you punch off a few claymores.  Instantly, your sleeping, exhausted brothers leap into action.  When dawn or the flares reveal a band of Rock Apes or Water Buffalo dead in the wire you feel sheepish or embarrassed, but your vigilance doesn't subside.<br>
It is a shame that Class Lass and Doc Del have been blasted in the wire by the very ones who love them...because of a cowardly bastard named Spatz.<br>
I recall a threat one night.  I had a platoon of men armed with M-14s and a limited amount of ammo.  We were facing a very real and large force.  We were in the open, in a shallow depression with little cover.  I knew that we were too few..and that our ammo would be exhausted very quickly. I whispered, &quot;Fix bayonets!&quot;  That command still rings in my ears. My principle concern was that one of my men would prematurely break discipline and start shooting.  The pressure was immense.  The charge came less than a click in front and to the right of us.  Eight inch guns charged with cannister rounds completely destroyed the large attacking force...and we never fired a single round from our paltry M-14s nor did we have to use our bayonets.<br>
Reflecting upon what happened to Class Lass and Doc Del sent intrusive thoughts running through my mind..there remains a need to be vigilant..the shooting has stopped..but the enemy lurks in the darkness.  The likes of Spatz remains a threat to traumatized veterans.<br>
My advice to my brothers is to hold their fire until they can clearly see the yellow of Spatz's back!<br><br>
Captain Edward Ramon - RVN '66'67'69    
